<h1>@HI{{te mo ii}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vte{{}} <strong>@HI{{mo ii}}</strong>
<li> @Aistem{{}}@HI{{kute}} <strong>@HI{{mo ii}}</strong>, ...
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{de}} <strong>@HI{{mo ii}}</strong>, ...
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{de}} <strong>@HI{{mo}}</strong>, ...
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
When this expression is used with a verb, it means permission is being granted.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{copy^true}}wo @KJ{{snapshot}}ttemo ii desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      You may take pictures.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{tall}}kute mo ii desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It's OK if it is expensive.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{study^life}}de mo ii desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It's OK if you are a student.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{ii(desu)}} can be replaced by @HI{{kamaimasenn}} or @HI{{yoroshii(desu)}}, with increasing levels of politeness.
</p>

<p>
With a WH word @HI{{te mo ii}} means "it is alright no matter WH".
</p>

